definition.value: A 1-(5-hydroxyhexyl)-3,7-dimethyl-3,7-dihydro-1H-purine-2,6-dione that has (S)-configuration. It is the inactive optical enantiomer of (R)-lisofylline, an anti-inflammatory agent.
A dimethylxanthine that is 3,7-dihydro-1H-purine-2,6-dione which is substituted at positions 1,3 and 7 by a 5-hydroxyhexyl group, methyl group and methyl group, respectively.
Any 3beta-hydroxy steroid which is substituted at the 4alpha and 4beta positions by methyl and hydroxymethyl groups, respectively.
A racemate comprising equal amounts of (R)- and (S)-lisofylline. It is a metabolite of pentoxifylline and a potent anti-inflammatory agent in which the (-)-isomer is biologically active.
Any 3beta-hydroxy steroid which is substituted at the 4alpha and 4beta positions by methyl and formyl groups, respectively.
Any steroid acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the 4beta-carboxy group of a 3beta-hydroxy-4alpha-methylsteroid-4beta-carboxylic acid.
Any 3-oxosteroid which is substituted by a methyl group at the 4alpha position.

A 3beta-hydroxy-4,4-dimethylsteroid that is that is cholestan-3beta-ol in which the hydrogens at position 4 have been replaced by methyl groups and a double bond has been introduced between positions 8 and 14.
A 3beta-hydroxy-4beta-hydroxymethyl-4alpha-methylsteroid that is 14-demethyllanosterol in which the methyl group at the 4beta position has been oxidised to the corresponding hydroxymethyl group.

A 3beta-hydroxy-4beta-formyl-4alpha-methylsteroid resulting from the formal oxidation of the 4beta-hydroxymethyl group of 4beta-hydroxymethyl-4alpha-methyl-5alpha-cholesta-8,24-dien-3beta-ol to the corresponding formyl group.

A 3beta-hydroxy-4alpha-methylsteroid-4beta-carboxylate resulting from the deprotonation of the carboxy group of 3beta-hydroxy-4alpha-methyl-5alpha-cholesta-8,24-diene-4beta-carboxylic acid. The major species at pH 7.3.
A steroid acid anion that is the conjugate base of 4alpha-carboxyzymosterol, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.

Major species at pH 7.3. The structure is based on the fact that all (except one; see Wikipedia page for anthocyanidin) anthocyanidins have OH groups at positions 3,5,7,4' and can be substituted at positions 3' and 5'

A member of the class of quinolines that is quinoline substituted by a methyl group, 3-fluoro-2-(2-hydroxypropan-2-yl)phenoxy group, fluoro group and fluoro group at positions 2, 3, 7 and 8, respectively. It is a fungicide being developed by Nippon-Soda Co. Ltd (Japan) which has stable efficacy against a wide range of plant diseases, such as gray mold, scab and rice blast.
A fatty alcohol consisting of a hydroxy function at any position of an unbranched saturated chain of five carbon atoms.
A hexosyl ceramide with C17iso branched chain sphingoid base and C22:0(OH) N-Acyl. Sum formula is C45H87NO9
A hexosyl ceramide with C17iso branched chain sphingoid base and C24:0(OH) N-Acyl. Sum formula is C47H91NO9
A hexosyl ceramide with C17iso branched chain sphingoid base and C26:0(OH) N-Acyl. Sum formula is C49H95NO9
A hexosyl ceramide with C17iso branched chain sphingoid base and C21:0(OH) N-Acyl. Sum formula is C44H85NO9
A hexosyl ceramide with C17iso branched chain sphingoid base and C23:0(OH) N-Acyl. Sum formula is C46H89NO9
A hexosyl ceramide with C17iso branched chain sphingoid base and C25:0(OH) N-Acyl. Sum formula is C48H93NO9
A dihydroceramide with C17iso branched chain sphingoid base and C22:0 N-Acyl. Sum formula is C39H79NO3
A dihydroceramide with C17iso branched chain sphingoid base and C24:0 N-Acyl. Sum formula is C41H83NO3
A dihydroceramide with C17iso branched chain sphingoid base and C26:0 N-Acyl. Sum formula is C43H87NO3
A dihydroceramide with C17iso branched chain sphingoid base and C22:0(OH) N-Acyl. Sum formula is C39H79NO4
A dihydroceramide with C17iso branched chain sphingoid base and C21:0 N-Acyl. Sum formula is C38H77NO3
A dihydroceramide with C17iso branched chain sphingoid base and C23:0 N-Acyl. Sum formula is C40H81NO3
A dihydroceramide with C17iso branched chain sphingoid base and C25:0 N-Acyl. Sum formula is C42H85NO3

A carbobicyclic compound that is bicyclo[3.2.1]oct-6-ene which is substituted by a methylene group at position 3 and by methyl groups at the 1,2,4,5,6,7, and 8-anti positions. It is the major volatile component released by the rhizobacterium Serratia odorifera.
